('134', '28/04/2011 00:00', 'Barbara', 'She had repeated burglaries to police but did not feel matter had been resolved. She and her husband thouhgt it was a spitirual attack and that they could only get through with prayer and staying close to God, daily reading of Bible. She mentioned self-harming and some releif therefore of prayer. I said we would pray and try to find professional advocate but did not think we would be successful. Mrs. Lawrence thanked me for listening and our prayer.', 'O', 'Responded to phone contact. Mrs Lawrence spoke about her response to Kath''s recent home visit. I said I could not comment on this. I listened while she spoke about her experience of her former Elim Church, Norfolk, but did not go into detail. Spoke about experiences since moving to Lancaster but again without detail. How she felt hurt and felt could not go into the same situation again.', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'FALSE'),
('134', '06/04/2011 00:00', 'Barbara', 'Mrs Lawrence phoned concerned that we have not contacted her. Apologised. They had put their cat due to the trauma of the burglaries. Mrs. Lawrence feels burden on her and is concerned for her medical condition - angina and recovering from cancer. Feels unable to cope with situation. They attended Ellel but did not find that helpful. They seem to be housebound because of fear of going out-consequence of burglaries. Phoned CAB - no answer. Victim Support - no response. Help Direct. Phoned Mr & Mrs. Lawrence and gave contact no. For victim support 01772828422 and said we would continue praying.', 'O', 'Help direct phoned back. We could contact police to see if vulnerable couple if victimised there is a process of help that can be given.', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'FALSE'),
('134', '02/06/2011 00:00', 'Barbara', 'I returned Brenda''s call. She gave me an update. She had contacted victim support as suggested, but the lady was unable to help advised seeing doctor. She believed they needed church fellowship but due to her previous experience in Norfolk had found it difficult. However on Sunday had gone to the Methodist church near their home and spoken to some of the women following the service over tea/coffee. The minister had visited her the next day, Brenda said she was ''stunned'' and ''shocked''  by the response. The minister suggested the doctor also. Brenda repeated that the trauma of previous encounter with medical proffession made it difficult if not impossible to seek medical help. She repeated feeling alone with no family or any other woman to talk to. She said she had been ''beaten'' and ''abused'' and ''bullied'' all her life. She looked to the church to help her. I drew her attention to celebrate recovery - reading from the leaflet. (I said I was quoting) and askedif she would like me to send her leaflet.', 'O', 'Leaflet sent in post that evening. N.B. Has been looking for church since 1988, in Norfolk took it to higher authority.', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'FALSE'),
